# Code Standards

## Core Principle
Always find the **simplest, most minimal correct solution** before writing any code.
Before implementing anything, ask: "What is the least amount of code that solves this correctly?"
Prefer editing existing code over adding new code. Prefer small, focused changes over rewrites.

## TypeScript
- No `any` — ever. Use `unknown` and narrow it, or define a proper type.
- All API response shapes must have a typed interface in `src/types/`.
- Infer types where possible — don't declare what TypeScript can already figure out.

## API Calls
- All HTTP calls go through `src/services/` only — never `fetch` or `axios` directly in a component or hook.
- Services return typed data or throw a typed error — no raw response objects leaked upward.

## Components
- Before creating a new component, check `src/components/` — reuse or extend what exists.
- A component does one thing. If it needs a comment to explain what it does, split it.
- No inline styles — Tailwind classes only.

## DRY
- Any logic used more than once goes into `src/hooks/` (React logic) or `src/utils/` (pure functions).
- Any repeated JSX pattern becomes a component.
- Never copy-paste — abstract first.

## Environment & Secrets
- All config via `.env` — no hardcoded URLs, keys, or credentials anywhere.
- Access env vars only through a single `src/config/env.ts` file — never `process.env` or `import.meta.env` scattered across files.

## Testing
- Write a unit test for every new component and every utility function.
- Test behaviour, not implementation — assert what the user sees or what the function returns.

## What Not to Do
- Do not run lint, build, migration, or database commands.
- Do not add abstractions, files, or dependencies that aren't immediately needed.
- Do not refactor working code unless directly asked.